This was discovered when trying to get Noda Time to work, but I've cut it down to a small reproducible example.

Blazor version: 0.3

Start off with the demo project (I've called mine `BlazorDemo`). Add the following code in a new file:

```csharp
namespace BlazorDemo
{
    public struct Instant
    {
        public readonly Duration duration;

        public Instant(Duration duration) => this.duration = duration;

        public static bool operator <(Instant left, Instant right) => left.duration < right.duration;
        public static bool operator >(Instant left, Instant right) => left.duration > right.duration;
    }

    public struct Duration
    {
        public readonly int days;

        public Duration(int days)
        {
            this.days = days;
        }

        public static bool operator <(Duration left, Duration right) =>
            left.days < right.days;
        public static bool operator >(Duration left, Duration right) =>
            left.days > right.days;
    }
}
```

In a Razor page, add this code:

```text
@{
    var duration1 = new Duration(-16777216);
    var duration2 = new Duration(16777215);
    var instant1 = new Instant(duration1);
    var instant2 = new Instant(duration2);
}

<p>Local duration comparison: @(duration1 < duration2)</p>
<p>Instant comparison: @(instant1 < instant2)</p>
<p>Duration-of-instant comparison: @(instant1.duration < instant2.duration)</p>
```

It *should* give the same result three times. The *actual* result is True, False, False.

If you change `Instant` to a class, it's fine. Using the local variables is fine. Even copying the duration values out of `instant1` and `instant2` and into new local variables works.

The problem isn't in Razor pages themselves - in my real code, the comparison is being checked within Noda Time, and it fails there too. I suspect this is a problem within the WASM version of Mono, but I dread to think where.

